How to finance the green transition
NEW YORK – This week, world leaders have gathered in New York at the United Nations to assess the global war on climate change and submit new commitments to reduce emissions.
The climate crisis is severe, and our pace of action is far from sufficient.
We are struggling to shift into high gear.
Accelerating the pace of change requires cooperation and effort from both public and private sectors.
Fortunately, thanks to the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), private-sector cooperation to combat climate change is increasingly prevalent.
Under the leadership of UN Special Envoy for Climate Action Michael Bloomberg, the CFLI was established with the aim of mobilizing private capital globally to address this critical issue.
This month, the CFLI released a new report titled "Financing the Low Carbon Future," outlining how to expand green finance to support an orderly low-carbon economic transition and identifying public-private partnership opportunities to achieve the Paris Climate Agreement goals in 2015.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects worldwide.
But now, responding to the call of European heads of state and the newly elected President of the European Commission Ursula von der Leyen, we are prepared to step up our ambition and strengthen the EIB's role as a specialized climate bank within the EU.
EIB will mainstream climate considerations, targeting low-carbon investments, and commit to investing at least one trillion euros over the next decade for low-carbon projects.
To achieve this, at least 50% of EIB financing will be directed towards climate action and environmental sustainability by 2025.
By the end of 2020, we will align all our financing activities with the goals of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects dependent on fossil fuels.
In addition, we will position the EIB as a green finance incubator, dedicated to mobilizing other resources to help economies transition to a low-carbon future.
As a European Union bank, our task is to invest in Europe's future, and the most pressing issue is undoubtedly climate change.
The more urgent the climate crisis, the stronger our resolve.
This summer, European countries have endured record-high temperatures and crop failures due to last year's drought.
Many developing countries have had similar experiences.
Floods and other climate-induced phenomena cost major cities billions of dollars annually, and threaten even more lives.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, as financing new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that plagues cities around the world.
Changing investment models could accelerate the shift away from fossil fuels, which has already begun.
Market forces are increasingly favoring clean energy over fossil fuels.
In 2011, half of America’s coal-fired power plants were retired, while the clean energy sector created 3.3 million jobs, compared to less than 100,000 in the coal industry.
In addition, more and more U.S. cities and states have pledged to achieve net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will be supported by Beyond Carbon, a initiative launched last year by the Bloomberg Philanthropies aimed at decarbonizing the entire US economy.
As an international community, we must not only invest in clean energy but also reduce investment in dirty energy.
Currently, in terms of fossil fuel subsidies, we are essentially spending money to promote climate change and air pollution.
This public funding should be directed towards technologies that can drive the green transition, such as electric vehicles.
These investments will yield huge returns, including reducing the significant costs associated with air pollution on public health.
Moreover, we can take many steps to direct the necessary funds.
First, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, companies and investors have been unaware of climate-related risks, unsure about the rationale for reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from extreme weather impacts.
This is starting to change.
The recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding companies to allocate capital more sustainably and allowing investors to reward those that seriously address climate change.
Secondly, we must clarify investment risks associated with green finance.
Cities account for more than 70% of carbon dioxide emissions, but only a few developing world cities can obtain credit ratings.
As a result, the total investment in clean public transport, energy-efficient buildings, and other projects that reduce emissions has been affected.
Governments and listed banks must step up efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including through initiatives like the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-led by the Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Thirdly, we need to modernize our power grids.
Incentives such as refunds and tax breaks have promoted the expansion of wind and solar power, reducing costs for businesses and consumers.
Now we should introduce similar programs to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies to address the intermittency issues more quickly.
In addition, better grid connectivity could allow regions with excess wind and solar power to supply areas with insufficient capacity.
Governments can play a leadership role in both areas, encouraging more private investment in clean power.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, since when the green bond market has grown to $136 billion.
But compared to a global bond market worth $100 trillion, this is just a drop in the ocean.
Therefore, the EIB is helping the EU develop sustainable finance standard classifications so that investors can compare similar projects, much like standard bonds.
Better and more detailed information about investment carbon footprints would enable investors to make informed decisions, thereby driving more private investment towards low-carbon projects.
This is how we finance the green transition.
